===Etymology===
From {{der|en|NL.|Ūtopia}}, the name of a fictional island possessing a seemingly perfect socio-politico-legal system in the book ''{{w|Utopia (book)|Utopia}}'' (1516) by {{w|Sir Thomas More}}. Coined from {{m|grc|οὐ||not}} + {{m|grc|τόπος|t=place, region}} ({{cog|en|topos}}) + {{der|en|la|-ia}}/{{der|en|grc|-ία}}, {{m|grc|-εια}} ({{cog|en|-ia}}).<ref>Craig, John (F.G.S.). [https://books.google.com/books?id=vuAOaDdR5IEC&pg=PA1001&dq=%22eu%22+%22topos%22+%22utopia%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjPxo-xjaTXAhWK2BoKHbFEAR4Q6AEIQDAE#v=onepage&q=%22eu%22%20%22topos%22%20%22utopia%22&f=false A New Universal Etymological, Technological, and Pronouncing Dictionary of the English Language, Embracing All the Terms Used in Science, Literature and Art]. Vol. II. George Routledge & Company, 1858, p. 1001</ref>

